                p181 <blockquote><q>The great mathematician Chu Shih-chieh朱世杰, trained in the northern school, migrated south to Yang-chou, where his books were printed but he could find no disciples. In consequence, the more sophisticated of his achievements became incomprehensible to following generations. But the basic scientific texts at least were common property everywhere.</q></blockquote><div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>p194 <blockquote><q>By Ming times, there was no one left who could understand the more advanced positional algebra of the Chin Tartar and early Yuan periods;...</q></blockquote>
