...The Chinese rural economy was becoming linked with the market mechanism. Trade was no longer just the supplier of luxuries (as in Han), but also the provider of necessities.
...the creation of a national internal customs network, which replaced the system of market regulation as the means by which the state controlled and taxed commerce.
</q></blockquote><div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>p167-168 （農業）地域分工。<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>p169 <blockquote><q>The growth of a system of local markets was both consequence and cause of this commercialized peasant economy.</q></blockquote><div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>p170 區域（interdependence between localities）<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>p175 <blockquote><q>The economic advances just described culminated in an urban revolution...城市化（人口（比例）激增）... urban landownership first bacame an important source of profit in Sung times, and urban real estate a specific and separate object of taxation.</q></blockquote>
